  },
  {
    "id": "m24_item3",
    "text": "The derivative of \\(\\tan^{-1}\\left(\\dfrac{\\sqrt{x}}{1+\\sqrt{1-x^2}}\\right)\\) with respect to \\(\\sec^{-1}\\left(\\dfrac{1}{2x^2-1}\\right)\\) is",
    "options": [
      "\\(\\dfrac{1}{2}\\)",
      "\\(\\dfrac{1}{4}\\)",
      "\\(-\\dfrac{1}{4}\\)",
      "\\(-\\dfrac{1}{2}\\)"
    ],
    "correctIndex": 2,
    "explanation": "Let \\(x=\\cos\\theta\\). Then \\(y=\\tan^{-1}\\left(\\dfrac{\\cos\\theta}{1+\\sin\\theta}\\right)=\\tan^{-1}(\\sec\\theta-\\tan\\theta)=\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}-\\dfrac{\\theta}{2}\\).\n\nAlso, \\(u=\\sec^{-1}\\left(\\dfrac{1}{2\\cos^2\\theta-1}\\right)=\\sec^{-1}(\\sec2\\theta)=2\\theta\\).\n\n\\[\\frac{dy}{du}=\\frac{dy/d\\theta}{du/d\\theta}=\\frac{-1/2}{2}=-\\frac{1}{4}\\]",
    "name": "Derivative of Inverse Trig with Substitution"
  },
  {
    "id": "m24_item4",
    "text": "If \\(x^{2019}\\cdot y^{2020}=(x+y)^{4039}\\), then \\(\\dfrac{dy}{dx}=\\)",
    "options": [
